  "doc_id": "45511",
  "text": "Urease activity test (rubescence was observed on urea agar slant). belongs to the T. mentagrophytes complex. In tinea faciei, the fungus is the most frequently isolated dermatophyte, usually linked to contact with rabbits. [CITATION_1] In China, T. interdigitale infections have increased significantly and are associated with animals. 8 The strain isolated from our case was macroscopically characterized by a beige, powdery surface and presented microscopically with numerous, thinwalled clavate macroconidia and round microconidia. These morphological features, combined with the strong inflammatory legion, indicate the zoophilic characteristics of the isolate in this case, which may originate from the rabbit. 9 The Api Zym system revealed that T. interdigitale was capable of producing multiple, extracellular enzymes, similar to those previously reported. [CITATION_2] These main secreted enzymes may be associated with damage to host tissue such as hair and skin. [CITATION_3] In addition, tinea faciei is prone to presenting with atypical features, probably due to the complex anatomy of the face.",
